   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div style=\"color: steelblue; font-size: 14px;\">\n",
    "\n",
    "**Variance Inflation Factor (VIF):** this quantifies the multicollinearity warning statsmodels flagged in Model 3. A VIF of 1 means no correlation with the other predictors; above 5 is generally considered moderate-to-high multicollinearity, and above 10 is a serious concern. None of our variables cross 5. log_income is highest at 4.01, followed by poverty at 3.66 (both expected, since income and poverty move together), while exercise_access (1.82), food_env (2.16), uninsured (1.26), and rural (1.84) are all low. This suggests the \"condition number is large\" warning in Model 3's output is likely driven more by the very different scales of our variables (income in tens of thousands of dollars vs. exercise_access bounded between 0 and 1) than by genuine multicollinearity. Either way, this confirms our main variable of interest, exercise_access, is not meaningfully entangled with the other predictors, which is why its estimate stays stable and significant across all three models."
   ]
  },
