    "<div style=\"color: steelblue; font-size: 14px;\">\n",
    "<b>The table above shows all three models side by side. Reading across the exercise_access row shows the same coefficient-stability story as the table further down: the estimate shrinks sharply from Model 1 to Model 2 (-0.076 to -0.028) when income enters, then changes only modestly to -0.035 in Model 3. It's also significant at the 1% level (***) in every single model, meaning the exercise-access effect isn't just stable in size, it's consistently distinguishable from zero throughout. Worth noting from the stars: not all of Model 3's added controls pull their weight equally. Poverty (***) and rural (***) are both highly significant, uninsured is only marginally significant (*, the 10% level), and food_env isn't statistically significant at all. So the \"barely changes R²\" result from adding these controls is really being driven mostly by poverty and rurality, not the full set evenly.</b>"
   ]
  },
